{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657672"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:33:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:33:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20641"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20641"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13517"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94158"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13517","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13517"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20641"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77258"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11578"},{"type":"tags","id":"11742"},{"type":"tags","id":"12529"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32281"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32282"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94158","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/94158"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMitochondria are essential organelles that evolved from ancestral prokaryotes and contain their own DNA. They are responsible for cellular energy production through oxidative phosphorylation and play important roles in apoptosis and intermediate metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the inheritance pattern of mitochondrial DNA?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Biparental inheritance","Autosomal recessive inheritance","X-linked inheritance","Maternal inheritance","Autosomal dominant inheritance"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMitochondrial DNA exhibits \u003Cstrong\u003Ematernal inheritance\u003C/strong\u003E patterns because the egg cell provides virtually all cytoplasmic components, including mitochondria, to the zygote after fertilization. Since new mitochondria develop from existing mitochondria, the offspring\u0027s mitochondrial genome is determined by the mother\u0027s lineage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other inheritance patterns are incorrect for mitochondrial DNA:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBiparental inheritance\u003C/strong\u003E - Although paternal mitochondria enter the egg during fertilization, they are typically destroyed, preventing contribution of paternal mitochondrial DNA to offspring.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutosomal recessive inheritance\u003C/strong\u003E - This pattern applies to nuclear genes on autosomes requiring two mutated copies for phenotypic expression. While nuclear genes affecting mitochondrial function may follow this pattern, mitochondrial DNA itself does not.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EX-linked inheritance\u003C/strong\u003E - This pattern applies to genes on the X chromosome. Nuclear genes on the X chromosome may affect mitochondrial function, but mitochondrial DNA exists separately from chromosomes.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutosomal dominant inheritance\u003C/strong\u003E - This pattern applies to nuclear genes on autosomes where one mutated copy is sufficient for phenotypic expression. While nuclear genes affecting mitochondrial function may follow this pattern, mitochondrial DNA itself does not.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that while mitochondrial DNA is maternally inherited, mitochondrial disorders can follow various inheritance patterns (X-linked, autosomal, or maternal) because mitochondrial proteins are encoded by both nuclear and mitochondrial DNA.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Mitochondria are derived from prokaryotes engulfed by primitive eukaryotes 1.5 billion years ago, explaining why they contain their own DNA.","Mitochondrial DNA is maternally inherited because the ovum contributes most cytoplasmic organelles to the fertilized zygote.","Mitochondria are dynamic organelles that undergo constant fission and fusion, with half-lives of 1 to 10 days before being degraded through mitophagy."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 1, The Cell as a Unit of Health and Disease; p. 15-16"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77258"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20641"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77258","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77258"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-23T12:42:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-23T12:43:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13517"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94158"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11578"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"The cell as a unit of health and disease","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":0,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T15:05:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T15:05:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"